provides unique insight into the personal nature of spirituality in recent times and how ancient and modern spiritual strands were harnessed to the needs of late-modern spiritual seekers. This book addresses debates about the complexity and meaning of the rise or decline of religion in the twentieth century and the processes involved in the formation of popular nontraditional spiritualities. It informs our understanding of global and transnational religions and recent forms of spiritual healing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChristian communitieszEnglandzBedfordxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and religionzEnglandzBedfordxHistoryy20th century. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology of Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Esotericism and Gnosticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : History of Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847287440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472874/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles